@jamesbyrd3740 

Yes, this is correct. I know it sounds dumb, because the way it's presented in software is very misleading and unintuitive, but saying that moving the voltage slider down doesn't decrease voltage is correct.

Moving the voltage slider down is the same thing as setting a +MHz offset on the core clock for Nvidia in Afterburner or other similar programs. The operating voltage will decrease slightly under load once you apply the offset, but not nearly by the amount that you punched in in your settings. V-drop is due to the new curve reacting differently to the load. You even see voltage drop slightly under load on Nvidia when applying a positive clock offset due to the same phenomenon, assuming you were power-limited the whole time in both cases.

